To open a website and remove any occurrence of `location.replace(url)` from the JavaScript code, you can modify the HTML content in a web page using JavaScript. Here is an example of how to achieve this:

Suppose the HTML content of the web page is as follows:

```
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Website Title</title>
    <script>
      location.replace("https://blockedsite.com");
      // more JavaScript code here
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Welcome to Website</h1>
    <p>Some text goes here..</p>
  </body>
</html>
```

You can remove the `location.replace()` function call from the JavaScript code using the following JavaScript:

```
// Open the web page
window.open('https://example.com', '_blank');

// Modify the HTML content
document.querySelectorAll('script').forEach(s => {
  let content = s.innerHTML;
  content = content.replace(/location.replace\(["'].*?["']\);/g, '');
  s.innerHTML = content;
});
```

This JavaScript code opens the web page specified in the `window.open()` method in a new tab. It then selects all the `<script>` elements in the HTML code using the `document.querySelectorAll()` method. For each `<script>` element, it replaces any occurrence of `location.replace(url)` using the `replace()` method with a regular expression that matches `location.replace("...");` or `location.replace('...');` and removes it from the HTML content. The modified code is then updated by replacing the original HTML content with the modified content using the `s.innerHTML = content` line.

Note that modifying the content of a web page can have unexpected consequences, and that you should only modify web pages that you are authorized to modify.

