var script = newWindow.document.createElement(‘script’);
script.src = ‘js/myScript.js’;
newWindow.document.head.appendChild(script);
};
 this code newWindow.document.write("hi"); not working

The reason why `newWindow.document.write("hi");` is not working is because the `document.write()` method overwrites the entire contents of the document when it is called after the initial page load. Therefore, when you call `newWindow.document.write("hi");` inside the `onload` function, it is replacing the contents of the `document` object with just the string "hi".

To avoid overwriting the contents of the new window, you can replace `document.write()` with another method to modify the content of the window, such as `document.body.innerHTML`. Here's how you can modify your code:

```
var newWindow = window.open('https://www.google.com/');

newWindow.onload = function() {
  newWindow.document.body.innerHTML = "hi";

  var script = newWindow.document.createElement('script');
  script.src = 'js/myScript.js';
  newWindow.document.head.appendChild(script);
};
```

In this example, the string "hi" is inserted into the `innerHTML` property of the `body` element of the `document` object. This method allows you to add new content to the window without overwriting the entire document.

As I mentioned earlier, creating a web proxy using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript alone is not recommended as it requires server-side scripting. However, here's a simple example of how you can create a basic user interface for a web proxy using HTML and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Web Proxy</title>
  <style>
    /* CSS styles for the user interface */
    body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
    }

    h1 {
        font-size: 30px;
        margin: 20px;
    }

    input[type=url] {
        width: 80%;
        padding: 10px;
        margin: 20px 0;
        border-radius: 5px;
        border: 1px solid #ccc;
        font-size: 16px;
    }

    button {
        padding: 10px 20px;
        background-color: #4CAF50;
        color: white;
        border: none;
        cursor: pointer;
        border-radius: 5px;
        font-size: 16px;
    }

    button:hover {
        background-color: #3e8e41;
    }

    iframe {
        width: 100%;
        height: 500px;
        border: none;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Web Proxy</h1>
  <form>
    <input type="url" placeholder="Enter a URL to load" id="url">
    <button type="button" onclick="loadUrl()">Load</button>
  </form>
  <iframe id="iframe"></iframe>
  <script>
    function loadUrl() {
      var url = document.getElementById("url").value;
      document.getElementById("iframe").src = "https://cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com/" + url;
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the user enters the URL they want to load into an input field, and when they click the "Load" button, the URL is appended to the `cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com` URL to form a proxy URL. The `iframe` element then loads the content from the proxy URL.

However, please note that this is a very simple example and is not secure, and it is only for demonstration purposes. A fully functional web proxy requires much more than what this example provides.

